public class File extends BaseWritableResource implements FileSystemObject
File abstraction that adds integrates files with the KivaKit resource mini-framework and adds a variety of useful methods. File system service providers for this abstraction are in com.telenav.kivakit.filesystem.local (the local filesystem provider) and in the kivakit-filesystems module.

Creation

Files can be created with several static factory methods, including:

  • parseFile(Listener listener, String)
  • parseFile(Listener, String, VariableMap)
  • file(Listener, URI)
  • file(Listener, FilePath)
  • file(Listener, java.io.File)

    • materialized

      public File materialized(@NotNull @NotNull com.telenav.kivakit.core.progress.ProgressReporter reporter)
      Materializes this file: if the file is remote, it is copied to the local filesystem and that file is returned. Materialization is necessary because some files, such as zip and JAR archives cannot be accessed as resources since they are random access. It is necessary to materialize such files before accessing them. Another reason to materialize a file is to improve performance if a file is to be read more than once.
      Specified by:
      materialized in interface Resource
      Overrides:
      materialized in class BaseReadableResource
      Returns:
      This file, or if it is remote, a file on the local filesystem that has the contents of this file

    • safeCopyFrom

      public void safeCopyFrom(@NotNull @NotNull Resource resource, @NotNull @NotNull CopyMode mode, @NotNull @NotNull com.telenav.kivakit.core.progress.ProgressReporter reporter)
      Safely copies to this virtual file from the given resource. Copies this readable resource to the given file safely (ensuring that a corrupted copy of the file never exists). This is done by first copying to a temporary file in the same folder. If the copy operation is successful, the destination file is then removed and the temporary file is renamed to the destination file's name.
